Source: Angola Press online, Thu 31 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.angolapress-angop.ao/noticia-e.asp?ID=329783>

Angola: Death Toll In Marburg Hemorrhagic Fever Outbreak now 126
--------------------------------------------------
The death toll of the Marburg hemorrhagic fever outbreak has risen over the
last 24 hours from 117 to 126, out of the 132 cases recorded in Angola's
northern Uije province.
This was announced in Luanda on Wed 30 Mar 2005 by the Deputy Health
minister. Speaking to the press, the Deputy Minister explained that 5 of
the new corpses were found in residential areas by health staff working on
the detection of new cases of infection in the region. The bodies were
taken to the mortuary and buried subsequently, without giving the
next-of-kin the chance to handle them, the source said. According to him,
at this stage, the province has made some improvement in the isolation of
the sick, with aid of the Medicins sans Frontieres running the ward.
2 experts of the World Health Organisation (WHO) have left for the
country's northern region, carrying laboratory equipment capable of
detecting viruses. To fight the "Marburg" virus, the province is currently
counting on the aid of 4 experts, 2 with WHO and the others from Canada,
plus 17 with Medicins sans Frontieres.
As to Cabinda province, the 16 people who were in direct contact with the
case from Uije are under the control of the health authorities.
