[3]
Date: Thu 31 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ABC News online, Agence France Presse report, Thu 31 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200503/s1335693.htm>

Angola: Death Toll May Have Reached 130
---------------------------------------
Angola's Health Ministry and the World Health Organisation have said 126
people had died between 13 Oct 2004 and 30 Mar 2005 from the deadly
Ebola-like Marburg virus, making it the world's worst [Marburg fever]
outbreak by official count.
"We have recorded a total of 132 cases between 13 Oct 2004 and 30 Mar 2005,
of whom 126 have died," a joint statement said. An earlier government toll
had put the number of cases at 124 and the fatalities at 117. But
unofficial estimates by health workers and officials earlier said the
number of deceased totalled 130, surpassing the previous record.
A severe form of haemorrhagic fever akin to Ebola, Marburg virus was first
identified in 1967. It spreads on contact with the fluids the body produces
in reaction to it, such as blood, urine, excrement, vomit and saliva. The
outbreak has claimed a record number of lives, overtaking the earlier peak
in the Democratic Republic of Congo, Angola's neighbour.
But Quiala Godi, the number-2 health official in the northern province of
Uige -- the epicentre of the virus -- said the toll was higher in that area
alone. "I don't agree with the figures given by Luanda," he told AFP over
the telephone. "Until yesterday, we had a total of 132 cases, including 125
dead in the provincial hospital of Uige [alone] without counting 5 bodies
elsewhere."
Meanwhile, a communique by Angola's health ministry, the WHO, Medecins sans
Frontieres and the UN children's agency UNICEF said Canada had sent a
mobile laboratory to investigate cases of the virus. 4 African nations --
The Democratic Republic of Congo, Congo-Brazzaville, Kenya and the western
island country of Sao Tome and Principe -- have gone on alert in the wake
of the outbreak in Angola.
Luanda's provincial health director Vita Mvemba on Monday appealed for
international assistance, saying the southern African country, which only
recently emerged from a brutal 27-year civil war, had only 1200 doctors
nationwide. 3/4 of the deaths in Angola have been children under the age of
5 years, according to the WHO, but the virus has also started to claim
adult victims since it erupted in October 2004.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to the WHO update (see [1] above) the reported case fatality
rate in this outbreak is 96 percent (127 deaths out of 132 cases). As
mentioned it is the highest case fatality rate reported in known outbreaks
of Marburg fever. It is still early in the course of the epidemiologic
investigation, and it is possible that with active case surveillance in the
region that milder cases that have not come to the attention of the health
sector will be identified. We await further information as it becomes
available. - Mod.MPP]
